      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks, that's much clearer. So, if I'm understanding correctly, this clause essentially places a lot of \"hidden\" risk on me for things that might not even be my fault if the client's own actions caused the breach. Is there any way to limit this liability so it isn't so one-sided? Like, can I negotiate to cap the amount I'd have to pay or limit it to just \"direct\" damages?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you've got the gist of it. To address your concern, it is indeed possible to negotiate terms within a contract to limit your liability. You can propose amendments to the indemnification clause to make it more balanced. For example, you could suggest capping the amount you would be responsible for or specifying that your liability should only cover \"direct\" damages, which are the immediate and direct consequences of your breach, rather than \"indirect\" or consequential damages, which could be more extensive and harder to predict.\n\nWhen negotiating such terms, it's important to clearly define what constitutes \"direct\" damages and to agree on a reasonable cap that reflects the potential risks involved in the project. It's also advisable to consult with a legal professional who can help you draft these amendments and ensure that they are legally sound and enforceable. By doing so, you can work towards a more equitable arrangement that protects both parties' interests.",
